[
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Benson Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "1 Kings 11:11-13",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "1 Kings 11:11-13",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Wherefore the Lord said unto Solomon — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Probably by some prophet. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "I will surely rend the kingdom from thee, and give it to thy servant — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Namely, Jeroboam, whom God permitted to rise into power and influence, that he might take the greatest part of his kingdom from him. This was enough to astonish Solomon, or any man, to hear that all his splendour should be so soon eclipsed! ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Notwithstanding, in thy days I will",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "not do it — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Or, not suffer it to be done; for in this sense these expressions are to be taken. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "For David thy father’s sake — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "For my promise made to him. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "But will give one tribe to thy son — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The tribe of Judah. Benjamin was not entirely his, but part of it adhered to Jeroboam, as Beth-el, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 12:29",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; and Hephron, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 13:19",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; both which were towns of Benjamin. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "For David my servant’s sake — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Who, though he was guilty of great sins, yet never forsook God to follow the abominations of idols; nor ever swerved long from God’s commandments, but made haste to repent and amend his ways, whenever he offended. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "And for Jerusalem’s sake which I have chosen — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Not literally, for the sake of the city Jerusalem, but for the great and precious purposes to mankind in general, which God intended to bring about, in his divine providence, by keeping up the knowledge of himself at Jerusalem.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Matthew Henry's Concise Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "11:9-13 The Lord told Solomon, it is likely by a prophet, what he must expect for his apostacy. Though we have reason to hope that he repented, and found mercy, yet the Holy Ghost did not expressly record it, but left it doubtful, as a warning to others not to sin. The guilt may be taken away, but not the reproach; that will remain. Thus it must remain uncertain to us till the day of judgment, whether or not Solomon was left to suffer the everlasting displeasure of an offended God.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Barnes' Notes on the Bible",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Chemosh (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Numbers 21:29",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " note), seems to have been widely worshipped in Western Asia. His name occurs frequently on the \"Moabite-Stone.\" Car-Chemish, \"the fort of Chemosh,\" a great city of the northern Hittites, must have been under his protection. In Babylon he seems to have been known as Chomus-belus, or Chemosh-Bel.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The hill - Olivet. At present the most southern summit only (the \"Mons Offensionis\") is pointed out as having been desecrated by the idol sanctuaries: but the early Eastern travelers tell us that in their time the most northern suburb was believed to have been the site of the high p ace of Chemosh, the southern one that of Moloch only. ",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "The hill - Olivet. At present the most southern summit only (the \"Mons Offensionis\") is pointed out as having been desecrated by the idol sanctuaries: but the early Eastern travelers tell us that in their time the most northern suburb was believed to have been the site of the high p ace of Chemosh, the southern one that of Moloch only. ",
            "children": []
